Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
What I like so much about this movie is that even though it's an X-Men movie, it's not really a superhero film. At least not in the traditional sense. If I had to categorize it, I'd call it a tragic western more than anything. A fascinating play on genres, and proof that Marvel (and DC) should try branching out from plain old superhero flicks to more complex movies like this one.


(Keep in mind, I say that as a fan of superhero movies in general. I find them great. But they are getting a little repetitive, and I feel like Logan proved beyond a doubt that mixing things up is absolutely a great way to continue the stories that can be told about so many of our favorite characters.)

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
The marriage of genres has never been quite as perfect as this since maybe The Dark Knight. But whereas the Dark Knight combined the moral tale of a hero with both an urban crime story and a Socratic meditation on utopia, *Logan* combines the moral tale of a hero with a classic western, the ethical apathy of corporate culture, and a metaphoric tale about fighting one's demons. 



Logan's intricacy baffles me in this today's culture of passable big-budget entertainment. In 2008, audiences were at least primed to the possibility of The Dark Knight becoming a masterpiece because it followed the release of Batman Begins and was directed by the great Christopher Nolan. 



But Logan?? The film's brilliance literally came out of left field since The Wolverine by James Mangold was a decent film, but not a masterpiece.

gli tagliamo e li buttiamo agli cani.. observi che sono vari segmenti dolorosi.. il dolore piu grande e inanzitutto per me il furto che ho hanno fatto da me... ricordati gli diavoli(come nell tuo x-men) fanno sparire tutte le risorse le mie monete.. le tue.. quelle di america etc.. e io gli voglio mettere in galera.. inutile avere persone senza limiti.. tutti con lo stesso motto in bocca-fanno qualunque cosa e in qualsiasi modo tutto.. questo articolo di legge dovrebbe essere la pastiglia mortale per gli animali che la leccano la justizia romena dice.. che perdona questo comportamento.... ma vai a farti ficare qualcosa nell culo.so che non dovrei scriverti cosi a tinte forti  perche sono una bella ragazza e puoi dire che non mi sta bene invece devo mettere limiti agli cani che mi mordono il corpo... senza il mio consentire.. ti ho racontato che tariceanu(il diamante nero) non so che cazzo di ministra prepara per voi gli gattini(gattini aristocratici - il fumetto).. so che e solo in mezzo a zingari pericolosi per questo a fatto un aleanza strana per vedere da dentro il bubbone il male(the bad thing and peaople).. io sto perdendo il controlo della propria esistenza perche da sola non riesco ad risolvere.. provero andare a haga all inizio di giugno.. anche prima.. sono triste.. stanca e in pericolo.. il fatto di sapere che ho quasi gli tuoi problemi ma in una zona con pocchissimi amici per me significa terriorismo..il effetto su di me e devastante.. metti tutto questo un foglio e studia. non so come aiutarti di piu cosi voi avete minus problemi.non perdermi di vista devi capire la mia situazione, farmi questo piccolo piacere. abbracci.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: This movie, in December, is still holding it's own as one of the best films of 2017. This movie is flawless. There is NOTHING bad about it. You can tell that a great deal of effort and ambition was put into the making of Logan. The attention to detail, the cinematography, the sound, the score, the script, and the performances were all beautifully executed. Hugh Jackman gave what may as well be his greatest performance of his career. I loved every minute of him on screen, as well as Patrick Stewart and Dafne Keen. Boyd Holbrook, Stephen Merchant, and all of the supporting actors were also phenomenal. The story was beautiful. This trailer alone! Hurt by Johnny Cash was a perfect fit and for the tone of the movie. I didn't know about the song until I saw the trailer.. and mannnn am I glad I didn't know! I now identify Hurt with Logan. I was overwhelmingly obsessed with it after I first saw it. This is a great trailer for a great movie. Respect to James Mangold and the producers! One of the best superhero comic book movies ever made👊👊👊 #Masterpiece

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Just seen the movie for the first time, and it just moved Wolverine up from being my #2 favorite superhero of all time to co #1 alongside Batman. This man has been through so much throughout his life, and has lost everyone he's ever loved. But under that rugged and pissed off demeanor lies a heart of gold. He gave his last to save a bunch of kids and his daughter of only a week. That is what a true superhero is. As far as the movie, it is perhaps both the goriest and most emotional superhero movie I've ever seen. Which makes it the perfect Wolverine movie. I don't think there's ever been an actor more fit to play a superhero role than Hugh Jackman as Wolverine. He IS Wolverine. And I hope his years of hard work and dedication to the role pays off with Logan in the form of at least an Oscar nom. In fact, I got serious Leo DiCaprio in Revenant vibes from Jackman here. Anyway, phenomenal movie.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Imagine if all the superheroes were killed leaving behind all super villains and various horrible monsters as well as any interesting gadget's the superheroes might have used now scattered across the world like the gadgets in the Fallout games. Which is an appropriate analogy since everything logically would go very Mad Max. Which is exactly what happened in the Old Man Logan comic books which this film is based on. I'm dramatically disappointed. The world of Old Man Logan, may be more interesting than Fallout. But in the film the Marvel universe has actually become less interesting. It's like watching an old Wolverine wander around our universe. Before you down vote me take a moment to read one of the comics. It doesn't even matter which one. Just pick up a random Old Man Logan comic book and you'll see what I mean.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Just watched the film last night. I don't know much about the X-Men, or even Wolverine in that matter, but he's definitely rubbing off on me in a good way. Probably one of my favorite superheroes. This movie was really good. It's different than typical superhero movies and it doesn't even feel much like one. It's more raw, more deep, more painfully truthful. The portrayal of Logan really is something. He's such a brutal and conflicted character, and it's definitely shown. It's quite sad and dark, but that's what makes it memorable. Absolutely would not recommend for kids, but that makes sense, what with the R rating. I think it's a good thing they decided to go the extra step by adding the violence and language and make it have that rating, because they were able to show a more truthful and realistic depiction of what Logan is really like. It brought out that roguish, animal, angry, brutish, human realism of what he is. And that is when you know you have a great film: the actors and writers and directors and EVERYONE involved are able to make a believable and pure character.

Comment: I am not a X-men fan nor specifically of Wolverine.  But this movie showed the Human side of Wolverine which caught my attention.  And how Hugh Jackman has grown wise and connected with the Character on his final portrayal (what seems to be) of Wolverine.  Above all, It shows the chemistry between a Father and a Daughter and how one sacrifices for another in the journey.  No superficiality, no faked emotions, and no superhero fashion and fantasies.  Hugh Jackman & Patrick Stewart will be remembered for their deep character portrayals and the Human side of them.  Hats Off to the Crew who made the movie.  The IMDB rating of the movie may be a little hyped up.  But it's worth a watch.  Cheers.

So I've seen the movie..

I don't think I've ever felt so overwhelmed, emotional-exhausted and stunned after watching a comic book movie.
This movie was almost to the level of being flawless. It did not feel like a comic book/X-Men movie at all. It was so different. The tone was different. It was unique, it was special and it was effective.
Hands down to the cast, especially the performances of X-23, Charles Xavier and obviously Logan. All of them were amazing! X-23 is so badass!
I'm so happy how the movie was made and ended the characters of Hugh Jackman and Patrick Stewart. Thank you for playing Wolverine and Professor X!

I recommend to all of you to watch it!
This is the one.

Comment:
*SPOILERS*

Just saw the movie. It is better than all the other Wolverine movies. I especially loved the performance of the actress playing X-23 (and didn't even guess that's who the character was) and the killing of those guys in the hotel.

However, I was confused about why there were no more mutants except that the chief villain was somehow involved (although I did forget to stay for the after-credits scene).

I also disliked some obvious cliches like how Logan, time after time, gets surprised when the people tracking him find them. You would think a master tracker like Logan would know not to stay with that family because it would put them in danger. I know Professor X wanted it, but Logan should've had the discipline to deny it and go eat at a nice restaurant with all that money and stay in a nice hotel.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Logan, at least for me, ended the *superhero* *genre* *phenomenon* that ironically started all the way back with X-Men in 2000. I feel like every subsequent superhero movie won't feel the same after this film. Along with Hugh Jackman (the man who's been with us through the entire run of comic book movies dominating Hollywood), Logan represented the fatigue of being a hero and, nearing the end, finding one last thing to fight for and discovering *inner* *peace.* I'm not saying I won't see any more comic book movies after this, but I believe I've found the perfect resolution to this phenomenon and don't think any subsequent movie in this genre will feel the same. You couldn't end it any better.

Comment:
As a Wolverine fan since his first stand-alone film, this movie will take you on one last ride with Hugh Jackman. Words cannot explain how much I never wanted this movie to end. The action, thrills, and new concepts that were brought into this movie left my jaw dropping (and I don't usually drop my jaw during movies). 

It left an emotional wound on my heart, and this movie will leave you crying your heart out, i tell you. One last moment of the series, and the movie has executed that out all so perfectly.

People tell you most movies they see are good, but this one breaks the barrier for everything. 

The emotions that every single person in the theater had was like a disease; We all had it. 

I could have never been happier to see an ending like that ❤️

Comment:
I hope that the fact that we see Wolverine older and to a certain extent a bit more "vulnerable" will be explained in the movie ... but I find the fact seeing him strangely older, and fans forgive me for using the following word that I don't like using when I think of Logan, also "weaker"great. 
It adds a high flavour of realism to the movie. 
Mutants being wiped out is also intriguing (biological contagious "weapon"??).
Maybe Wolverine survived as he is the only mutant whose cells can heal quickly?  But still, we see Professor Xavier who is also a mutant (btw excellent concept to see him alongside with Wolverine) that offsets the theory that X Men were wiped out by a sort of biological weapon targeting mutant genes. 
Anyway, Logan movie is very promising and from what we saw from the trailers, is far better than the two previous ones. The story reminds me of one of the first X Men movies where he just wants to stand alone by himself and does not care nor believe much about Xavier's school but then get softened and feel forced somehow to help a young girl. Here, the end magically matches the begin and here, he is a 100 times stronger even if he has been somehow weakened by something but he fights with his strongest skill... : his guts and it is just what Wolverine is about before any mutant power. He never gives up.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
I'm a bit mixed about this trailer. I adore this song, might even be my all time favourite, so there's that. But on the other hand I'm not a fan of all these superhero movies we got lately because even though we saw it could be amazing with stuff like Guardians of the Galaxy or Batman, most producers are in a purely commercial aim and waste the huge potential of these franchises, and we know how much potential a superhero movie can have !

And this time on one hand it seems it's gonna be different, more subtle and dramatic (without cutting the action), but on the other hand they took the same film-maker they took for the last Wolverine, that had more of a commercial aim than the very bests like Batman or GOTG.
And on one hand this song is absolutely amazing, but on the other hand taking this song for a trailer is CHEATING ! This song is so amazing you can make anything slightly dramatic look amazing and give you the chills if you put that song over it !

Comment: This had better live up to expectations. Let's face it the X-Men movie franchise isn't what it used to be. I did not see the wolverine so I can't comment on how this will be compared to that. I'm sure Age of Apocalypse was a decent movie but Days of Future Past left so much to be desired. I get where they're going with this in focusing solely on Wolverine now and it's good to see Patrick Stewart back but I'll have to wait to see the reviews come March to decide of this is going to be worth my time to see an old man Logan film, which is what this is. Don't get me wrong Wolverine is a good character and I've always liked Hugh in the role but the last few movies in the franchise just feel like they don't know where the X-Men movie franchise is going anymore. They should stick to Logan only for a while and sort out which person is Professor X and which continuity they want to follow.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
This trailer really gets to me. Almost every part that Professor X is shown reminds me of my late grandfather. From 0:32 the way he's looking at the ceiling is the same way my grandfather would look up at the ceiling when we was depressed. 1:09 reminds me when my dad would carry my grandfather to bed at night because he couldn't move his legs anymore. 1:12 the way Xavier turns and smiles is exactly how my grandfather would move too. It doesn't help that granddad looked like Professor X and my cousins and I would pretend we were other X-Men and play with him when we were really young...

This trailer is beautifully made. It shows raw emotions! 
Can't wait!!!!

Comment:
Well, so much for the whole plot and outcome of Days of Future Past, because it seems like everything's ruined again. This seems to have the same problem with The Force Awakens which is ruining a grand and emotional victory (failures of Luke's New Jedi Order and the New Republic after RotJ, "Charles the Mutants are gone" after DoFP). Don't get me wrong, the tone of the trailer was interesting and I think it can be good on its own, but it already seems to have ruined DoFP, the fantastic conclusion to the old cast's story. I haven't read Old Man Logan so if I'm missing something please let me know.

EDIT: I saw in some of the other comments that Cable will fix everything in Deadpool 2 or X-Force. If that what they're planning and if it's good then I might forgive this movie. Sadly Star Wars doesn't have this luxury and it's legacy is ruined forever.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Well this film looks real promising, and I'm not just saying that because I've re-watched the trailer a few-dozen times.

There's something emotionally profound about Logan's powers diminishing. Imagine someone who's essentially been immortal finally nearing mortality. He's been lost much of the time, enduring pain and loss, and essentially becoming numb to life's endless repetition. Now that he's losing his abilities, he's forced to reflect and wonder if he's wasted that time, and perhaps he'll finally find more of a reason to care and keep living just as that's being taken away.

This film could be great, and has a lot of character-driven potential. Even if it isn't, I think I'll still appreciate the break from the stereotypical superhero movie outing. I've been subject to a degree of superhero fatigue, so it's nice when they focus on something different, and the filmmakers really try to make an actual film rather than just a product. Yep. I'll stay optimistic though.

Almost like Fox is making this movie with the intent that it can stand on its own as an awesome western that will be remembered more about the characters than being an X-Men movie. It's also like they wanted this to be remembered as a standalone classic movie that can be watched without ever having seen previous X-Men movies. A perfect way for Hugh Jackman to unleash the claws one last time and Stewart to unleash the mind one last time.

Comment:
For anyone who doesn't know what timeline this is this is after the events of X-men Apocalypse. This is the chronological order...
First Timeline
1. X-men First Class
2. X-men Wolverine Origins
3. X-men
4. X-men 2
5. X-men The Last Stand
6. Wolverine Immortal
7. First minutes of the movie X-men Days of Future Past

Second Timeline and it's the timeline they are on now
8. After Mystique decided not to kill Trask in X-men Days of Future Past a new timeline was created

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Odd how seeing fictional characters you've grown up watching on the big screen, over time turn old. Almost as if you believe they are immortal as the characters they play. I was 13 when X-Men was released and I was so tuned into the whole super hero universe. Watching this trailer made me feel old now and how time just keeps on going with or without you. I didn't expect the feels while watching this but I'm glad it triggered them in me. It seems they are giving Logan a good farewell, Hugh Jackmans dedication to the roll has been nothing short of amazing in my books. Staying in tip top shape for 17 years? Can't wait to see this, I'll probably have to bring sun glasses to the theater though since it will be hard saying goodbye.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
Part of me really wants to see Anna Paquin return as Rogue one last time for at least one moment or scene with Logan. 
Paquin and Jackman started the entire X-Universe back in 2000 together, and it'd be cathartic to see them end it together, or for Jackman's end in the series at least. 

It'd create a really bittersweet book ending of the series. She doesn't even need to be alive, akin to Famke Janssen's scenes as Jean Grey in the previous Wolverine movie. 

Wishful thinking for the poetry and emotion of it. Rogue was Logan's first charge in the movie universe after all.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
God, does this look amazing! First trailer that I've teared up on in a while. Jackman has been an amazing Wolverine; it's going to be devastating to see him go. Jackman's Wolverine is not only my favorite superhero, but also one of my favorite film characters altogether. Not to mention that Hugh seems to be a cool guy himself; I really hope him leaving has nothing to do with the rumors about his health. Also, as someone who grew up with and loved the X-Men Evolution TV series, getting to see one of its original characters (X23) have a major film appearance is awesome - the show always seemed to go under the radar so this is a nice nod as a legacy for the show.

All it needs now is Liev Schreiber to return as Sabertooth. Yes, I know that Origins is considered to be a bad movie by most and is technically out of the continuity, but Liev played a great role for what he had to work with, and I'm sure they can still fit him in somehow. Since, filming is done, even if its just a voice or at the last minute they film a flashback - it would be awesome to see a last scene between the two.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment:
It's not hard to figure out at all if any attention is paid to the movies while watching them. 

Old timeline: Origins Wolverine (pre-60s parts) First Class, Origins Wolverine (rest of the movie), X-Men, X2, The Last Stand, The Wolverine, Days of Future Past (dark future). 

New timeline: Origins Wolverine (pre-60s, but not mentioned), First Class, Days of Future Past (Wolverine changing the timeline), Apocalypse, next X-Men movie, unknown events altered through the 00's (X-Men 1, 2 and 3 erased), Days of Future Past (light future), Logan. 

Deadpool just floats in existence because it's self-aware, and doesn't pinpoint itself at an exact moment in the timelines. But it's safe to assume it's in the new timeline, because Origins Wolverine post-60s no longer exists.

Mister Hugh Jackman , sir, I can appreciate that this is your last outing as Logan and I wish to comment that I've been ready for you to stop playing him as you have been misrepresenting him in every movie since the very beginning. Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Knowing that this will be Hugh Jackman's last role in the X-Men films makes me so sad. I remember watching bits and pieces of the x-men movies since I was little and they've always been one of my favorite series'. The Avengers, in my opinion, can never surpass them. The x-men paralleled the plight of mutants with so many political movements in our world's history and they truly created a wonderful series with full of lasting messages. While I'm a fan of the prequels as well, the originals and the Wolverine movies will always hold a more special place in my heart. I'm tearing up right now just thinking about watching this in theaters, so I now for a fact that I'll be sobbing once March actually rolls around. I'm just glad I won't be the only one.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: I'm actually quite impressed by the type of storyline the producers are implementing in this movie. It has sort of a "The Last Of Us" vibe to it. That scene where the girl, Logan, and Xavier are laughing around the dinner table touched my heart deeply. I'm also glad that Logan and Xavier get to spend quality time with each other. I am however frustrated that the movie is yet again about a dystopian future. Don't get me wrong, I love stories about dystopian futures, but I thought that the X-men already averted a previous dark future. All in all, I love the look of this feature film and I plan to see it in theatres. I already watched The Wolverine, so why not watch Logan? Another thing, I loved was the use of the Johnny Cash song Hurt. I appreciate it because I loved Johnny Cash and I'm an avid fan of Nine Inch Nails and Trent Reznor. Also I think I might have to read some of the graphic novels regarding the X-men comics just to understand what's going on in the film franchise.

Comment: The X-Men series is really hit and miss, but when they make a hit, it is so much better than anything other comic related franchises have to offer. X2, First Class, Days of Future Past, and Logan are so much better than anything the MCU or DCEU has produced. Hugh Jackman is one of the best castings for any superhero because of his unparalleled dedication to the character. He stuck with Wolverine even in the worst parts of the franchise. Comment: By the time this comes out, I'll be 17. And it's crazy to think I've known and looked up this character, specifically Hugh's portayal, for my entire life. It's going to be really hard letting him go after 17 whole years. I feel Hugh Jackman's Wolverine is by far the most fleshed out character in comic book movie history. And it's not just the writing, or whoever is directing it. It's also because Hugh Jackman is such an amazing actor, and he has always done the character right. It will be sad to see Hugh step down from the Wolverine mantle, but I know it's what's right for his character. Whoever comes along in the future to play Logan will probably never be as good as Hugh Jackman.

I'd rather they have skipped Stewart and made this take place in eighteen years. With even some advanced healing abilities lingering, I'd assume he'd be better off than what Im seeing. Comment:
Wow, this is gonna be powerful. Not sure if I'm ready to say goodbye! But Jake Gyllenhaal would be a great fill-in. He's young, extremely talented and really incredible to watch on screen. Karl Urban could do a solid job. He's great at portraying an intimidating presence and grumpy mood, and same goes for Tom Hardy. Hardy is actually Jackman's personal pick to take up the mantel after him.

It still won't be the same seeing a different face in such a long-time role. It's been so long! Haven't felt this way about a movie since I had to say goodbye to Harry Potter in Deathly Hallows Pt. 2.

Title: Logan | Official Trailer [HD] | 20th Century FOX
Comment: Beautiful. This trailer got me as soon as Johnny Cash started playing. It leaves me with intrigue when professor delivers the line, "Logan, what did you do?". I can already imagine the possibilities. Patrick Stewart and Hugh Jackman will be greatly missed, I just can't picture anybody else portraying these characters. This looks very down to earth. You can feel Logan's mortality. You can see how exposed the world is, no more mutants. I love the idea of post-apocalypse. Like, once you get rid of something you've so greatly depended on for protection, or nurture, you begin to think what else can happen? But you see this little girl that seems to represent hope. I wonder if this will be as great as Days of Future Past? I can't wait to figure it out.

Comment:
Hmmm... I honestly don't know what to think of it. All the anti-superhero idiots will love the movie, sure... but, there is no fantastical element in this movie? I was wondering if the movie might would have the Blob appearing as a cannibal, have Sabretooth appear in a last showdown with Wolverine, and maybe even have a segment of Logan being thrown out to Savage Land and have to get back from there.
But nope. Make it completely grounded in reality outside of Wolverine's claws. God forbid anything else...

On the other hand, it does seem to be a good movie. I just tend to prefer movies building upon their shared universe as opposed to alienating it.
